          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
   The Geopolitics behind time zones
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/no-international-body-time-zone-choice.jpg" alt="With no international body in charge, countries can choose their own time zon" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>With no international body in charge, countries can choose their own time zone. Credits: The Economist</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px 6px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        Time zones can have geopolitical implications. The International Meridian Conference of 1884 laid the groundwork for a system of global time zones. However, over the years, <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-04-06-2025-political-factors" target="_blank">political factors</a> have affected them. Some countries often pick time zones for reasons beyond just solar accuracy. They might do this to assert sovereignty, align with allies, or distance themselves from rivals.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Some examples include:</p>
       </mj-text>
       <mj-table font-family="Roboto+Serif" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" padding="10px 18px" style=" width:100%;">
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">‚Üí</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.6;">
                     India adopted UTC+5:30 to differentiate itself from the British colonial time zone</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">‚Üí</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;line-height:1.6;">
                  North Korea has changed its time zone several times to assert its independence from South Korea and Japan</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">‚Üí</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;line-height:1.6;">
                   China uses Beijing Time for the entire country. This is to demonstrate centralized control, even though it spans five time zones </td>
            </tr>
             <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">‚Üí</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;line-height:1.6;">
                   Russia moved Crimea's time to match Moscow‚Äôs. Russia‚Äôs Kaliningrad Oblast, despite being situated between Lithuania and Poland, is set in Moscow time </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td style="font-size:18px; width:20px; vertical-align: top; padding-right:8px;line-height:1.6;">‚Üí</td>
              <td style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;line-height:1.6;">
                    Morocco adjusts its time zones during Ramadan to accommodate people during the fasting hours</td>
            </tr>
        </mj-table>
       <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">     
        In some areas, disputed borders create overlapping time practices. This reflects contested authority. Even choices about daylight saving time can hold diplomatic weight. Therefore, time zones aren't just logistical tools; they shape national identity and send a message.
        </p>
        </mj-text>
